9 An Act relating to public buildings and public works;
amending 61 O.S. 2021, Section 103, as amended by
10 Section 23, Chapter 228, O.S.L. 2022 (61 O.S. Supp.
2024, Section 103), which relates to the Public
11 Competitive Bidding Act of 1974; requiring local bid
preference for certain public construction contracts;
12 and providing an effective date.
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 61 O.S. 2021, Section 103, as
17 amended by Section 23, Chapter 228, O.S.L. 2022 (61 O.S. Supp. 2024,
18 Section 103), is amended to read as follows:
19 Section 103. A. Unless otherwise provided by law, all public
20 construction contracts exceeding One Hundred Thousand Dollars
21 ($100,000.00) or construction management trade contracts or
22 subcontracts exceeding Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) shall be
23 let and awarded to the lowest responsible bidder, by open
24 competitive bidding after solicitation for sealed bids, in
SB1014 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 acco rdance with the provisions of the Public Competitive Bidding Act
2 of 1974. No work shall be commenced until a written contract is
3 executed and all required bonds and insurance have been provided by
4 the contractor to the awarding public agency.
5 B. Notwithstanding subsection A of this section, in awarding
6 public construction contracts exceeding One Hundred Thousand Dollars
7 ($100,000.00) or construction management trade contracts or
8 subcontracts exceeding Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00),
9 counties, cities, other local units of government and any public
10 trust with a county or a municipality as its sole beneficiary may
11 shall provide for a local bid preference of not more than five
12 percent (5%) of the bid price if the awarding public agency
13 determines that there is an economic benefit to the local area or
14 economy. Provided, however, the local bidder or contractor must
15 agree to perform the contract for the same price and terms as the
16 bid proposed by the nonlocal bidder or contractor. Any bid
17 preference granted hereunder must be in accordance with an
18 established policy adopted by the governing body of the awarding
19 public agency to clearly demonstrate the economic benefit to the
20 local area or economy. Provided, further, no local bid preference
21 shall be granted unless the local bidding entity is the second
22 lowest qualified bid on the contract. The bid specifications shall
23 clearly state that the bid is subject to a local bidder preference
24 law. For purposes of this section, “local bid” means the bidding
SB1014 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 pers on is authorized to transact business in this state and
2 maintains a bona fide establishment for transacting such business
3 within this state. This provision does not apply to any
4 construction contract for which federal funds are available for
5 expenditure when its provisions may be in conflict with federal law
6 or regulation.
7 C. Except as provided in subsection E of this section, other
8 construction contracts for the purpose of making any public
9 improvements or constructing any public building or making repairs
10 to the same for One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or less
11 shall be let and awarded to the lowest responsible bidder by receipt
12 of written bids or awarded on the basis of competitive quotes to the
13 lowest responsible qualified contractor. Work may be commenced in
14 accordance with the purchasing policies of the public agency.
15 D. Except as provided in subsection E of this section, other
16 construction contracts for less than Ten Thousand Dollars
17 ($10,000.00) may be negotiated with a qualified contractor. Work
18 may be commenced in accordance with the purchasing policies of the
19 public agency.
20 E. The provisions of this subsection shall apply to public
21 construction for minor maintenance or minor repair work to public
22 school district property. Other construction contracts for less
23 than Twenty-five Thousand Dollars ($25,000.00) may be negotiated
24 with a qualified contractor. Construction contracts equal to or
SB1014 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 grea ter than Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) but less than One
2 Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) shall be let and awarded to
3 the lowest responsible bidder by receipt of written bids. No work
4 shall be commenced on any construction contract until a written
5 contract is executed and proof of insurance has been provided by the
6 contractor to the awarding public agency.
7 F. The Construction and Properties Division of the Office of
8 Management and Enterprise Services may award contracts using best
9 value competitive proposals. As used in this subsection, “best
10 value” means an optional contract award system which can evaluate
11 and rank submitted competitive performance proposals to identify the
12 proposal with the greatest value to the state. The Office of
13 Management and Enterprise Services, pursuant to the Administrative
14 Procedures Act, shall promulgate rules necessary to implement the
15 provisions of this subsection.
16 G. 1. A public agency shall not let or award a public
17 construction contract exceeding One Hundred Thousand Dollars
18 ($100,000.00) or a construction management trade contract or
19 subcontract exceeding Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) to any
20 contractor affiliated with a purchasing cooperative unless the
21 purchasing cooperative and the contractor have complied with all of
22 the provisions of the Public Competitive Bidding Act of 1974,
23 including, but not limited to, open competitive bidding after
24 solicitation for sealed bids. A public agency shall not let or
SB1014 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 awar d a public construction contract exceeding Ten Thousand Dollars
2 ($10,000.00) up to One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) to any
3 contractor affiliated with a purchasing cooperative unless the
4 purchasing cooperative and the contractor have complied with all of
5 the provisions of the Public Competitive Bidding Act of 1974,
6 including submission of a written bid upon notice of competitive
7 bidding.
8 2. A purchasing cooperative and its affiliated contractors
9 shall not be allowed to bid on any public construction contract
10 exceeding One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000.00) or any
11 construction management trade contract or subcontract exceeding
12 Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) unless the purchasing
13 cooperative and its affiliated contractors have complied with all of
14 the provisions of the Public Competitive Bidding Act of 1974,
15 including, but not limited to, open competitive bidding after
16 solicitation for sealed bids. A purchasing cooperative and its
17 affiliated contractors shall not be allowed to bid on any public
18 construction contract exceeding Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00)
19 unless the purchasing cooperative and its affiliated contractors
20 have complied with all of the provisions of the Public Competitive
21 Bidding Act of 1974, including submission of a written bid upon
22 notice of open competitive bidding.
23 3. Local governmental units, or local governmental units
24 cooperating under the terms of any interlocal cooperative agreement
SB1014 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 auth orized by state law, may create a purchasing cooperative or
2 contract with a purchasing cooperative to provide leverage in
3 achieving best value or the best terms in contracts. To encourage
4 intergovernmental collaboration, any purchasing cooperative or
5 interlocal cooperative entity may utilize any single legal newspaper
6 of this state to serve as sufficient compliance for bid notice
7 requirements of competitive bidding or solicitation of bids. If the
8 purchasing cooperative or interlocal cooperative entity is engaging
9 in a project exclusive to a county or group of counties of this
10 state, and not open to all governmental units or public trusts that
11 wish to participate statewide, the bid notice shall be published in
12 a legal newspaper located within the county or group of counties.
13 Any local governmental unit or public trust that enters into
14 membership or contracts with a purchasing cooperative or interlocal
15 cooperative entity may enter into purchases or contracts under the
16 terms negotiated by the purchasing cooperative or interlocal
17 cooperative entity. If the purchasing cooperative or interlocal
18 cooperative entity complies with the requirements of this section of
19 law, all local governmental units shall be deemed in compliance with
20 the requirements set forth for bid notices and publication.
21 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
